  "prompt": "As technology is growing day by day, what according to you didn't got online?",
  "response": "It's true that technology has made significant strides in digitizing various aspects of daily life. However, there are still some areas where the transition to online platforms has been slower or less effective. Here are a few examples:\n\n1. **Authentic Handmade Crafts**: While many artisans sell their work online, the full experience of handmade crafts, including the tactile and communal aspects, hasn't entirely been captured by digital platforms.\n\n2. **Certain Medical Treatments**: While telemedicine has grown, some medical treatments, diagnostics, and surgical procedures still require in-person interaction.\n\n3. **Physical Fitness and Sports**: Many sports and physical fitness activities, especially team sports or those requiring specialized equipment, haven't fully transitioned to online formats.\n\n4. **Agriculture**: While technology aids in various aspects of farming, the physical work of planting, tending, and harvesting crops hasn't been replaced by digital means.\n\n5. **Taste-Based Experiences**: Restaurants and culinary experiences can't be fully digitized as the sensory experience of taste and smell can't be replicated online.\n\n6. **Hands-on Education**: Practical and hands-on training for certain professions (e.g., lab work, trades, art) still predominantly requires in-person attendance.\n\nThese areas highlight the limits of technology in fully replacing physical presence or sensory experiences that are inherently tied to the real world.",
